pleted":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"If I have two files that look like this, `src/index.js`:\n\n```\nimport array from './module';\narray[0]();\n```\n\nand `src/module.js`:\n\n```\nconst array = [];\nfor (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    array.push(() => i);\n}\nexport default array;\n```\n\nthen run\n`mkdir -p tmp && babel src -b es6.modules,strict -d tmp && rollup -f iife -i tmp/index.js -o bundle.js`\n\nNow, `tmp/module.js` looks like this:\n\n```\nvar array = [];\n\nvar _loop = function (i) {\n    array.push(function () {\n        return i;\n    });\n};\n\nfor (var i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    _loop(i);\n}\nexport default array;\n```\n\nBut the output in `bundle.js` does not include the loop at all:\n\n```\n(function () { 'use strict';\n\n    var array = [];\n\n    array[0]();\n\n})();\n```\n\nIf I change the loop in `module.js` to simply `push(i)`, it works though. It seems that Rollup is not able to detect that the function Babel creates to get correct scoping for `i` will mutate `array`.\n\nThe only way I found to deal with this is to do something like this:\n\n```\nconst array = [];\n(function (array) {\n    for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n        array.push(() => i);\n    }\n})(array);\nexport default array;\n```\n\nAny chance that Rollup will be able to handle this without workarounds?\n","closed_by":{"login":"Rich-Harris","id":1162160,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjExNjIxNjA=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1162160?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Rich-Harris","html_url":"https://github.com/Rich-Harris","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Rich-Harris/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Rich-Harris/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Rich-Harris/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Rich-Harris/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.co